-- South Africa Stocks Fall Fifth Day in 6, Led By Anglo, BHP, Eqstra, Impala
-- Garth Theunissen
-- 2010-06-29T11:25:46Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-29/south-african-stocks-fall-fifth-day-in-six-led-by-anglo-american-implats.html

          
          
             South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index  declined for the fifth time in six days, sliding
325.43, or 1.2 percent, to 26,964.29 at 1:01 p.m. in
Johannesburg.  
 The following are among the most active stocks in the South
African market today.  
 Anglo Platinum Ltd.  (AMS SJ), the world’s biggest platinum
producer, dropped 18.30 rand, or 2.4 percent, to 751.20 rand.
 Impala Platinum Holdings Ltd.  (IMP SJ), the second-largest, fell
4.40 rand, or 2.3 percent, to 185 rand. The price of the metal
decreased as much as 2 percent in London trading.  
 BHP Billiton Ltd.  (BIL SJ), the world’s largest mining
company, fell 4.45 rand, or 2.1 percent, to 209.80 rand.  Anglo
American Plc  (AGL SJ) retreated 5.46 rand, or 1.9 percent, to
282.60 rand. Copper, lead, nickel and zinc declined on the
London Metal Exchange.  
 Eqstra Holdings Ltd.  (EQS SJ), an industrial and heavy-
equipment rental company, fell 5 cents, or 1 percent, to 5.05
rand. The company said it will report a loss in the fiscal year
through June 30 compared with earnings per share of 16.6 cents a
year earlier.  
 Simmer & Jack Mines Ltd.  (SIM SJ), a gold producer, slid 3
cents, or 3 percent, to 97 cents. Simmers posted a net loss of
638.9 million rand ($83.6 million) in the year through March
compared with a 2.6 billion-rand profit the year before.  
 Sasol Ltd.  (SOL SJ), the world’s biggest maker of motor
fuel from coal, fell 4.60 rand, or 1.6 percent, to 278.90 rand.
Oil for August delivery declined as much as 2.6 percent to
$76.25 a barrel in electronic trading in New York.  
